Data Engineering Case Study¶

Step 2: data cleaning¶

Previously we have downloaded BTCUSDT minute-level OHLCV data from binance.us using their API and saved to our sql database in Postgres. In this section I would like to go through some steps to analyze any discrepancies in the data.

class btcusdt_cleaner:
    
    def __init__(self,table_name,connection_params):
        self.table_name = table_name
        self.connection_params = connection_params
        self.df = None
        self.ts = None
        return 
    
    def get_data(self):
        engine = sqlalchemy.create_engine(
            'postgresql://{user}:{password}@localhost:5432/{dbname}'.format(**self.connection_params)
         )
        self.df = pd.read_sql_table(
            self.table_name,
            con=engine)
        return
    

    def get_ts(self):
        '''
        Extract minute-level time series data from dataframe. "Merge" open and close price.
        
        Output saved in self.ts
        
        Returns
        -------
        None.
        '''
        df = self.df
        close_px = df["close"]
        close_px.index = pd.to_datetime(df["close_time"],unit="ms").round("1min")
        close_px = close_px[~close_px.index.duplicated(keep='first')]

        open_px  = df["open"]
        open_px.index = pd.to_datetime(df["open_time"],unit="ms").round("1min")
        open_px = open_px[~open_px.index.duplicated(keep='first')]

        open_px = open_px.reindex(pd.date_range(open_px.index[0],close_px.index[-1],freq="1min"))
        close_px = close_px.reindex(pd.date_range(open_px.index[0],close_px.index[-1],freq="1min"))

        open_px[open_px.isna()] = close_px
        self.ts = open_px.to_frame()
        self.ts = self.ts.rename(columns={"open":"px"})
        return

Check 2: Outliers¶

Two checks for ouliers

  1. Look at distribution (histogram) of log returns;

  2. Look at price moving average and if prices "jump" out of their k-standard deviation bands.

Conclusion: safe to categorize log returns outside of [-0.02,0.02] are outliers. However, they appear to be real jumps instead of data errors.

We can also detect/visualize discontinuity with k-std moving average bands.

In [19]:
k= k1 = k2 = 10
w1  = 60
w2 = 300

ts["ma{w1}".format(w1=w1)] = ts["px"].rolling(window=w1).mean()
ts["ub{w1}".format(w1=w1)] = ts["ma{w1}".format(w1=w1)] + ts["px"].rolling(window=w1).std() * k1
ts["lb{w1}".format(w1=w1)] = ts["ma{w1}".format(w1=w1)] - ts["px"].rolling(window=w1).std() * k1
ts["%ma{w1}".format(w1=w1)] = ts["px"] / ts["ma{w1}".format(w1=w1)]

ts["ma{w2}".format(w2=w2)] = ts["px"].rolling(window=w2).mean()
ts["ub{w2}".format(w2=w2)] = ts["ma{w2}".format(w2=w2)] + ts["px"].rolling(window=w2).std() * k2
ts["lb{w2}".format(w2=w2)] = ts["ma{w2}".format(w2=w2)] - ts["px"].rolling(window=w2).std() * k2
ts["%ma{w2}".format(w2=w2)] = ts["px"] / ts["ma{w2}".format(w2=w2)]

Conclusion: the jumps are either sudden price movements following periods of very low volatility or "flash crashes". The recommended preprocessing depends on the business use. For prediction, many algorithms have loss functions that are sensitive to outliers, so we should "clip" the returns at these time points to say [-0.02,0.02]. For simulation, we want to model the frequency and maginitude of the "jumps", so we should keep them as raw values.

Conclusion¶

Putting everything together, I would recommend:

  1. Negative interval length / overlapping time intervals - drop (status = 2);

  2. Intervals of uneven width - keep, merge into one ts if there are > 1min gaps;

  3. Jumps - use k-std bands around moving average to determine outliers - keep, and label (status = 3);

  4. 0 volume, stale OHLC, repeated values - keep, but label as warning (status = 1);

  5. Missing ts data by reindexing - keep, but label as potentially interpolated data (status = 4).
